Now I understand the issue. Looking at the test, `readOfLength0ShouldReturn0`, it expects that calling `read(buffer, offset, 0)` should return 0. Let me check the current implementation of the `read` method:

The problem is in the `read(byte[] dest, int offs, int len)` method. According to the Java InputStream contract, when `len` is 0, the method should return 0 without doing anything. However, the current implementation doesn't handle this edge case properly.

Looking at the current logic:
```java
@Override
public int read(final byte[] dest, final int offs, final int len)
    throws IOException {
    if (offs < 0) {
        throw new IndexOutOfBoundsException("offs(" + offs + ") < 0.");
    }
    if (len < 0) {
        throw new IndexOutOfBoundsException("len(" + len + ") < 0.");
    }
    if (offs + len > dest.length) {
        throw new IndexOutOfBoundsException("offs(" + offs + ") + len("
                                            + len + ") > dest.length(" + dest.length + ").");
    }
    if (this.in == null) {
        throw new IOException("stream closed");
    }

    final int hi = offs + len;
    int destOffs = offs;
    int b;
    while (destOffs < hi && ((b = read0()) >= 0)) {
        dest[destOffs++] = (byte) b;
        count(1);
    }

    int c = (destOffs == offs) ? -1 : (destOffs - offs);
    return c;
}
```

The method correctly handles validation but doesn't return early when `len == 0`. According to the Java specification for InputStream.read(), when `len` is 0, the method should return 0 immediately.

